Machine Learning Competition: Predicting Car Insurance Claims

Erik Kollmer

8/8/2021

1 Introduction

This is my machine learning model building process for Zindis Autoinland Vehicle Insurance Challenge. The goal of the competition was to assist the African car company Autoinland in predicting whether or not a customer would file a vehicle insurance claim in the next three months. I identified this as a binary classification task, where a machine learning model could be built to identify if a customer would file a vehicle insurance claim. Thus, the target variable data only has two levels: 1 indicates an insurance claim was filed, 0 meaning not filed.

Without further ado, lets dive right in.

  1. There are more claim-filing customers with a policy end date of Dec 31, 2010 (77) than the claim-filing customers that bought a policy on Jan 1, 2010 (29), meaning that there is no guarantee these are the same customers from start to end.

It makes sense that the state data would be similar to the city data in terms of percentage. In other words, binning this State variable into Missing, Other, and Lagos categories would likely yield similar proportions if we were to do it for the City variable.

2.13 Summary

After examining each predictor variable, it looks like none will be used as-is. Thus, we will have to manipulate the variables and create new ones to get the most use out of them. In the next section, well do the following:

  • Trim the Age range and either impute, eliminate, or adjust the outliers
  • Create a policy length variable and examine its distribution across the target variable
  • Create bins for Gender, ProductName,Car_Category, Subject_Car_Make,City,State, and possibly No_Pol
  • Create luxury and country of import variables from Subject_Car_Make
  • Encode all categorical variables as numeric using methods like target mean encoding and one-hot encoding
  • Create interaction terms from the encoded variables

3 Feature Engineering

3.1 Age

How can we encode the outliers for Age (younger than 16, older than 102)?

  • We could label them NA, then impute those values with the mean, median, mode, or the predicted results from a k-nearest neighbors or regression model
  • Remove all the rows with missing Age values from the dataset
  • Label them all as -1
  • Bin Age into categorical variables (e.g.young drivers would be 20-25), then have a separate category for missing values

Note: Each of these methods was attempted and ran with a random forest model. Imputing missing values with -1 worked best.

raw_train$Age <- ifelse(raw_train$Age < 16 | raw_train$Age > 102, -1, raw_train$Age)
raw_test$Age <- ifelse(raw_test$Age < 16 | raw_test$Age > 102, -1, raw_test$Age)

3.2 Policy Length

Since we have Policy.Start.Date and Policy.End.Date, we can take their difference and create a new variable, which well call policy_length.

raw_train %<>% mutate(policy_length = as.numeric(as.Date(raw_train$Policy.End.Date) - as.Date(raw_train$Policy.Start.Date)))

raw_test %<>% mutate(policy_length = as.numeric(as.Date(raw_test$Policy.End.Date) - as.Date(raw_test$Policy.Start.Date)))

pol_length_freq <- data.frame(table(raw_train$policy_length, raw_train$target)) %>% 
  rename(PolicyLength = Var1, target = Var2)

pol_length_freq %>% arrange(-Freq)

It seems that the majority of policies are either year or half-year long. We can bin policies into these ranges, then plot the distribution to see if there is any noticeable difference between the target variable levels.

raw_train$PolicyLengthBin <- 
  case_when(raw_train$policy_length %in% 364:365 ~ "FullYear",
            raw_train$policy_length %in% 178:182 ~ "HalfYear",
            raw_train$policy_length %in% 89:93 ~ "QuarterYear",
            TRUE ~ "Other")

pol_length_freq2 <- table(raw_train$PolicyLengthBin, raw_train$target)

graphics::mosaicplot(pol_length_freq2, col = c("#EE82EE","#9400D3"), 
                     main = "Policy Length Binned - Distribution")

It does not seem that there is a significant proportional difference for the target variable between the full-year and other plans. The full-year plans seem to be overwhelmingly common.

3.3 Binning

By creating bins for some of the categorical variables, we can make categories useful that would not be otherwise by including them as part of a larger group.

3.3.1 Gender

raw_train$Gender_Bin <- 
  case_when(raw_train$Gender == "Male" ~ "male",
            raw_train$Gender == "Female" ~ "female",
            TRUE ~ "other")

raw_test$Gender_Bin <- 
  case_when(raw_test$Gender == "Male" ~ "male",
            raw_test$Gender == "Female" ~ "female",
            TRUE ~ "other")

gender_bin_freq <- table(raw_train$Gender_Bin, raw_train$target)

graphics::mosaicplot(gender_bin_freq, col = c("#808080","#2F4F4F"), 
                     main = "Gender Bin Distribution",
                     xlab = "Gender", ylab = "target")

The proportions between male and female policy buyers is almost the same. However, the other category has a larger proportion of claim-filing customers, so we can plan to test out this newly created variable in our model.

3.3.2 Number of Policies

We can do something similar for the No_Pol predictor. Sometimes a level of detail can be lost when converting a numeric variable to a categorical one, but we can try both and see which is better for model performance.

raw_train$No_Pol_Bin <- 
  case_when(raw_train$No_Pol == 1 ~ "1",
            TRUE ~ "1+")
raw_test$No_Pol_Bin <- 
  case_when(raw_test$No_Pol == 1 ~ "1",
            TRUE ~ "1+")

gender_bin_freq <- table(raw_train$No_Pol_Bin, raw_train$target)

graphics::mosaicplot(gender_bin_freq, col = c("#F9D79C","#F9AC28"), 
                     main = "No. of Policies Bin Distribution",
                     xlab = "No. of Policies", ylab = "target")

The mosaic plot shows a noticeable difference in proportion, so we should consider No_Pol_Bin as a possibly useful predictor.

3.3.3 Product Name

3.4 Car Make

A cars manufacturer tells us a lot about it: some brands target the everyday commuter, others cater to wealthier customers. Some prioritize safety more than others as well. Also, some car brands are bound to be more available in Nigeria than others. This is part of the reason why the mtcars dataset (included with base R) has become a staple to illustrate certain concepts. We will be creating three new variables from Subject_Car_Make: whether that brand is high-end, whether that brand is popular in Nigeria, whether that brand is ranked highly for safety, and a standard binned variable based on the proportions of the individual car makes.

3.5 Encoding Categorical Variables

Why do it? - Able to create interaction terms - Can examine correlations between variables - More suited for model building. Many algorithms (like xgboost) will only work with all numeric variables

Note: I attempted to encode the variables two different ways: one-hot encoding (i.e.creating dummy variables) and target mean encoding. The latter better improved model performance, so I will be giving a more detailed explanation of that process.

The function below takes the mean of the target variable for each category of a given variable. For example, out of the 7617 male customers, 6715 of them did not file a claim, and 902 of them did. The target mean would be calculated by adding 6705 0s and 902 1s, then dividing by the number of male customers (7617). The target mean encoded value for all males would then be: 902/7617 = 0.1181493.

I intentionally omitted PolicyLengthBin because it was dominated by policies that were for the full year.

tme <- function(var, new.name){
    raw_train %>%
        group_by({{var}}) %>%
        mutate("{{new.name}}" := mean(target)) %>% 
    data.frame()
}

raw_train <- tme(Gender_Bin, gender_tm)
raw_train <- tme(No_Pol_Bin, pol_tm)
raw_train <- tme(Car_Category_Bin, carcat_tm)
raw_train <- tme(State_Bin, state_tm)
raw_train <- tme(City_Bin, city_tm)
raw_train <- tme(Popularity_Bin, popularity_tm)
raw_train <- tme(Brand_Bin, brand_tm)
raw_train <- tme(Luxury_Bin, luxury_tm)
raw_train <- tme(Product_Bin, product_tm)

One clear feature of the plot is that luxury_tm, brand_tm, and popularity_tm are highly correlated. This is expected, as they were all variables created from the values of Subject_Car_Make. Additionally, correlations of 0.76, 0.71, and 0.76 respectively with carcat_tm is not surprising, as we would expect certain car brands to specialize in certain car types (e.g.Toyota produces more saloons/cars than jeeps, SUVs, or trucks).

There is also a weak positive correlation (0.37) between state_tm and pol_tm. This is unexpected, as there doesnt seem to be any apparent reason why the number of policies a customer bought and where they bought it should be related. Maybe one branch of the car insurance company has better salespeople than the other, or people living in a more urban area like Lagos feel the need to buy more policies.

Most important, target has a correlation of 0.24 with product_tm. While this is not incredibly strong compared to the correlations discussed above, it supports our discovery in the earlier exploratory data analysis that ProductName looked to have significantly different proportions across the target variable. Ultimately, predictors with strong correlations with the target variable will help us best develop a model for predicting its outcome.

3.6 Interaction Terms

Given these correlations, we can create appropriate interaction terms to attempt to improve model performance. We can examine the correlations between the interaction terms as well to see if there are any more interesting relationships between the predictors.

sub_train %<>% mutate(car_int = carcat_tm * brand_tm, 
                      person_int =  gender_tm * Age,
                      wealth_int = luxury_tm * state_tm,
                      pbrand_int = product_tm * brand_tm,
                      pbc_int = product_tm * brand_tm * carcat_tm,
                      cp_int = carcat_tm * product_tm,
                      ageprod_int = product_tm * Age,
                      pca_int = product_tm * carcat_tm * Age,
                      pbca_int = product_tm * brand_tm * carcat_tm * Age,
                      prodst_int = product_tm * state_tm)
sub_test %<>% mutate(car_int = carcat_tm * brand_tm, 
                     person_int = gender_tm * Age,
                     wealth_int = luxury_tm * state_tm,
                     pbrand_int = product_tm * brand_tm,
                     pbc_int = product_tm * brand_tm * carcat_tm,
                     cp_int = carcat_tm * product_tm,
                     ageprod_int = product_tm * Age,
                     pca_int = product_tm * carcat_tm * Age,
                     pbca_int = product_tm * brand_tm * carcat_tm * Age,
                     prodst_int = product_tm * state_tm)

cor_int <- cor(sub_train[,c(1:3,12:21)])

ggcorrplot::ggcorrplot(cor_int, colors = c("orange","white","orange"), lab = TRUE,
                       lab_size = 2, tl.cex = 9, 
                       title = "Correlation Matrix: Interaction Terms")

Because some interaction terms include the same predictor variables, it makes sense that they would have strong correlations with each other. For example, the Age and person_int have a correlation of 0.95 because person_int is Age * Gender.

Unlike the target mean encoded terms, where product_tm had the strongest correlation with the target variable (0.24), there are a few more interaction terms that have slightly better correlations with the target variable: pbrand_int (0.27), pbc_int (0.27), and cp_int (0.26). However, this is not surprising, given each of these interaction terms includes product_tm. In fact, the majority of interactions terms include product_tm, which explains the cluster of highly correlated values in the upper right corner of the correlation plot.

3.7 Summary

Through feature engineering, we have created several different variables for use in machine learning. These variables were created to identify possible trends between a certain predictor and the target variable, or between combinations of predictor variables and the target variable. While it will be unlikely that we will end up using all of the engineered variables in the model, we have several combinatorial options to choose from.

4 Machine Learning

When testing out various machine learning models in practice, the two metrics of highest importance are accuracy and speed. Building and training a neural network might create the most accurate model, but it takes an incredible amount of computer processing power. On the other hand, algorithms like decision trees, KNN (k-nearest neighbors) or Naive Bayes are fairly straightforward and thus computationally quick. In the middle are improvements on the more straightforward algorithms: random forests, adaptive boosting, and gradient boosting are all ways to improve on the rudimentary classifications by decision trees.

Our current task is binary classification with a relatively small dataset (the test set only has ~1200 rows), so we can afford to use some more computationally intensive methods. I will start by building a model using the k-nearest neighbor algorithm. This will allow us to quickly determine a baseline accuracy for the model. That way, as we add or drop new variables, we can run the new set of predictors through the algorithm again and compare it to the baseline model.

4.1 Pre-Processing

Before building the data through any sort of model, we should divide sub_train into a training and validation set. By creating a validation set, we can see what our model predicts for the target variable and evaluate its performance. If we simply trained our model on sub_train (the data frame we ended up with at the end of the Feature Engineering section), we would be blindly predicting the target variable for the test set, with no way to evaluate if our model did a good job or not. A good rule of thumb is that 75% of the training set is split into the new training set, and 25% goes into the validation dataset. Ill call them a and b, respectively.

set.seed(2041)
ndx <- sample(nrow(sub_train), .75*nrow(sub_train))
a <- sub_train[ndx,]
b <- sub_train[-ndx,]

Lets make sure the proportion of the target variable is similar between the training and test sets.

prop.table(table(a$target))
## 
##         0         1 
## 0.8811127 0.1188873
prop.table(table(b$target))
## 
##         0         1 
## 0.8748344 0.1251656

Looks good!

Because we are classifying the target variable into either a 0 or 1, we should convert it to a factor.

a$target <- as.factor(a$target)
b$target <- as.factor(b$target)

One way to improve the performance of a machine learning model out of the gate is to implement cross-validation. The caret package allows us to implement this seamlessly into the model with its trainControl() function.

ctrl <- caret::trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

In a similar way to how we split the data into training data into training and validation sets, cross-validation takes our new set of training data and runs the model on a randomly selected subset of it. This process is repeated the number of times specified in the number argument.

4.2 Baseline KNN Model

Great! We are ready to train the model.

set.seed(2041)
KNNmodel <- train(target ~ ., data = a, method = "knn", 
                  trControl = ctrl, metric = "Kappa")
KNNmodel
## k-Nearest Neighbors 
## 
## 9059 samples
##   20 predictor
##    2 classes: '0', '1' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 8153, 8154, 8153, 8153, 8153, 8152, ... 
## Resampling results across tuning parameters:
## 
##   k  Accuracy   Kappa    
##   5  0.8658803  0.1425704
##   7  0.8701868  0.1146719
##   9  0.8741603  0.1079409
## 
## Kappa was used to select the optimal model using the largest value.
## The final value used for the model was k = 5.

You can see how cross-validation was incorporated in the model above: about 8153/9059 (~90%) samples of the data were used to actually train the model. In addition, the caret package automatically selects which parameters are best for the KNN model. If we wanted, we could specify specific parameters using the expand.grid function. Details on what parameters can be specified for each model can be found in Max Kuhns package documentation.

Now we can see how the model performs when evaluated against the validation set.

set.seed(2041)
KNNpred <- predict(KNNmodel, b)
postResample(pred = KNNpred, obs = b$target)
##  Accuracy     Kappa 
## 0.8605960 0.1532537
pROC::auc(pROC::roc(b$target, as.numeric(KNNpred)))
## Area under the curve: 0.5576

First, what do these metrics mean?

  • Accuracy: measures how well the model classified the target variable (number of true positives + number of true negatives/ number of observations)
  • Kappa: measures how well the model classified the target variable compared to if the results were guessed randomly. In this context, we would compare the predicted results to a 50/50 chance that the target variable was a 0 or a 1.
  • Area under the curve: the curve is the ROC curve, which plots the true positive rate against the false positive rate. The AUC (area under the curve) measures the probability of the model ranking a random positive example higher than a random negative example against a logistic regression model. The more predictions a model gets correct, the higher its AUC value will be.

The validation set had a lower accuracy and higher Kappa value compared to the cross-validated model (Accuracy = 0.8658803, Kappa = 0.1425704). This could be because there were more data points using the entire training dataset instead of a cross-validated subset of it. As a result, the model was able to determine the results better than random chance.

4.3 Improving Model Performance

While an accuracy of 86% is pretty good, a low Kappa value of 0.1532 doesnt make this model much more useful than randomly guessing the target variable. There are a number of ways we can go about improving the performance of this model:

  • Use different algorithms to build the model
  • Oversample the minority class of the target variable (i.e.improve the dataset by sampling more customers that had filed a claim than there actually are)
  • Evaluate the model using other performance metrics than Kappa (ROC, Accuracy)
  • Try different combinations of predictor variables

Note: At this stage, the model building process becomes very iterative. Much trial and error is involved determining which methods work to improve the overall model, which work best with certain algorithms, and which weaken the model performance. To reduce the amount of code and knitting time needed for this document, several different models were tested outside of this document. The model outlined below is the best working one, according to the score it received when submitted to the competition website.

4.4 Best Working Model

Ultimately, I did not end up using many of the variables that were included as part of sub_train or sub_test. There is are only two interaction term: person_int, which is between gender and age, and car_int, which is between car category and car brand. Additionally, I converted all of the categorical variables to numeric using target mean encoding.

In the same way we did with the KNN model, we can split the training set into training and validation sets, a and b. We also can once again convert the target variables in each set into a factor.

set.seed(2041)
ndx <- sample(nrow(train), .75*nrow(train))
a <- train[ndx,]
b <- train[-ndx,]

a$target <- as.factor(a$target)
b$target <- as.factor(b$target)
levels(a$target) <- c("X0","X1")

Something we did not explore in the baseline model was oversampling. If we look at the proportion of the target variable classes again, we can see there is a significantly smaller proportion of customers that did file a claim (the 1s).

#initial proportions
prop.table(table(a$target))
## 
##        X0        X1 
## 0.8811127 0.1188873
#after oversampling
synth <- ovun.sample(target ~ ., data = a, method = "over", p = 0.24, seed = 2041)$data
prop.table(table(synth$target))
## 
##        X0        X1 
## 0.7565877 0.2434123

Once again, well establish our hyperparameters with 10 folds for cross-validation. This time, well also add the twoClassSummary function to compare performance metrics across the different folds.

set.seed(2041)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10,summaryFunction = twoClassSummary, classProbs = TRUE)
ctrl$sampling <- "up"

Now we can train the model with our oversampled data. I found that a random forest classifier worked best with this data, although I also tried xgboost (extreme gradient boosting) and adaboost (adapative boosting).

RFmodel <- train(target ~ ., data = synth, method = "rf", metric = "ROC",
                 trControl = ctrl)

The next step is to see how the model performed:

RFpred <- predict(RFmodel, b)
levels(RFpred) <- c(0,1)
postResample(pred = RFpred, obs = b$target)
##  Accuracy     Kappa 
## 0.7807947 0.2375762
auc(roc(b$target, as.numeric(RFpred)))
## Area under the curve: 0.656

The baseline model had an accuracy of 0.8605, a Kappa value of .15325, and an AUC of 0.5576. While its accuracy is better than the random forest model, this is deceiving. As discussed before, accuracy is the measure of how well the model classified the target variable based on a positive/negative rate. When evaluating the model, there are only two categories. If those categories were equally represented in the data (i.e.50/50 split), then the accuracy would be a more reliable metric. However, because the vast majority of customers did not file a claim, the model would follow suit and predict a similar proportion distribution.

Lets say you were at a fair and there was a bowl of 20 vanilla cookies and 2 chocolate cookies The attendant asks you to make a prediction of which type of fruit youre going to pull out. If you kept reaching in (with your eyes closed) and succesfully kept predicting that you would pull a vanilla cookies, youd be pretty accurate. However, this doesnt inherently mean you have some sort of magic ability to pick out the exact cookie you predicted. It just means the sample distribution is heavily tilted in your favor.

Instead, we can use the kappa value and AUC to better represent the model performance.

All thats left is to use our model to predict the target variable for our test set:

RFpred_real <- predict(RFmodel, test)
levels(RFpred_real) <- c(0,1)
prop.table(table(RFpred_real))
## RFpred_real
##         0         1 
## 0.8269551 0.1730449

This proportion distribution is about mid-way between the distributions for our normal training set and our oversampled training set. Initially, I thought this would have a bearing on the outcome, but it turns out that was not the case.
